All other sensory responses in the upper extremities were normal.
Motor NCS in the bilateral upper extremities were normal.

Concentric needle examination of the Right First Dorsal Interosseous, the Right Pronator Teres, the Right Flexor Pollicis Longus, the Right Triceps Brachii, the Right Flexor Carpi Ulnaris, the Right Biceps Brachii, and the Right deltoid muscles were unremarkable.
Electrophysiological Impression: This is an essentially normal study.
The mildly reduced left LAC response does not correlate with any clinical symptoms and likely arises from a technical cause and does not represent true pathology.

There is no convincing electrodiagnostic evidence of neurogenic thoracic outlet syndrome on either side, compressive mononeuropathies of the upper extremities on either side, or a right sided cervical radiculopathy.
